'''Crazy J''', designed and implemented by [[User:Blashyrkh]] in late 2025, is a crippled little brother of [[Lazy K]]. It resembles the syntax of its older brother (two of them, actually) and adds a new one, uses the same IO model (with tiny modification), but based on different set of combinators. Which makes it slightly... different.

To understand the semantics (and, probably, even the syntax) of the language it's recommended to get familiar with [[Lambda calculus]] and [[Combinator calculus]] first.

In some sense Crazy J may be considered a joke language, but it was created to get an answer to the serious question: is it possible to create Turing-complete combinator-based functional language using a non-complete set of combinators? And the answer is "yes"!

==Instructions==

Crazy J is based on '''non-complete''' IJ basis:

    I = λ x . x
    J = λ x y z w . x y (x w z)

Nevertheless, Crazy J is proven to be Turing-complete (by implementing [[Cyclic tag system]] in it).

==Syntax==

Crazy J supports three different syntaxes.
* Unlambda-like parenthesis-free syntax (inspired by [[Unlambda]] and [[Lazy K]]). A typical program looks like this (but usually much longer):
<pre class="rectwrap">
````j``j```jii`j`j``jii``jiiij```````j`j````jjii`j`j``jiii`j```jjiijj```j``jii``ji``jii`j`j``jii````j```jii```j``ji```ji``j``jiiii```jjii``j`jijii``jii
</pre>
* Combinator calculus syntax (inspired by [[Lazy K]]). The same program:
<pre class="rectwrap">
J(J(JII(J(J(JII))))(JII))IJ(J(J(JJII(J(J(JII)))))I(J(JJII))JJ(J(JII)(JI(JII))(J(J(JII))))(J(JII(J(JI(JI(J(JII)I)I))(JJII)(J(JI)J)))II(JII)))
</pre>
* [[Brainfuck]] mimic syntax (inspired by [[MIBBLLII]]). The same program (reminds of something, eh?):
<pre class="rectwrap">
-.<-.->.<->+-[--++[-.<-]<-->+[--++<-]--[-.[,.][-.<-]][-.+<,>+<,->[--++][-,-]<.->++.]]
</pre>

Whitespace is ignored. The rest of a string starting from <code>#</code> until the end of line is a comment and is ignored as well.

Contrary to Lazy K, Crazy J doesn't allow to mix styles: the actual syntax used is determined by the first non-whitespace and non-comment character. An empty program is treated as an identity function ([[cat]]).

===Unlambda-like syntax===

          Syntax                            Semantics
    
    Expr  ::= "i"                       (λ x . x)
            | "j"                       (λ xyzw . xy(xwz))
            | "`" Expr1 Expr2           (Expr1 Expr2)

===Combinator calculus syntax===

          Syntax                            Semantics
    
    Expr  ::= "I"                       (λ x . x)
            | "J"                       (λ xyzw . xy(xwz))
            | Expr1 Expr2 ... ExprN     ((Expr1 Expr2) ... ExprN)
            | "(" Expr ")"              Expr

