<sup>*</sup>Parsing order is a unique concept of this syntax mode. If ''left-to-right'' parsing order is active, source fragment <code>ABC</code> means <code>(AB)C</code>. In ''right-to-left'' parsing order the same string <code>ABC</code> is interpreted as <code>C(BA)</code>. Parsing order doesn't change when <code>[</code> is encountered ("inherited" by sub-expression), but if it's changed between <code>[</code> and <code>]</code>, it's restored after <code>]</code> (similar to environment variables of Unix processes: inherited by children, never passed to parent).

==IO model==

''Almost'' exactly as of Lazy K. To be precise:

* Input is Church list of Church numerals where each element represents single byte of input stream. Contrary to Lazy K, ASCII character 0 is represented as Church numeral 1, ASCII character 1 - as Church numeral 2, and so on. The input stream is terminated with Church value 257 infinitely repeated.
* The program is called as a function with the input list passed as a parameter.
* Result of program evaluation must be a Church list of Church numerals. First value greater than or equal to 257 marks the end of output. This value minus 257 is the program's exit code. ''Output list is never examined beyond EOF'', and it's not just implementation detail as of Lazy K. It's essential part of Crazy J specification.
* Input is as lazy as possible: next byte is read from standard input only when it's needed to apply it to an argument.

Church numeral 0 is impossible in IJ basis, and therefore all input codes are incremented on input and decremented back before output.

==Lack of K combinator==

Whereas Lazy K's motto is "there's more than one way to do it", Crazy J's motto is "there's no way to do it, but we do it anyway."

To be precise:

* No constant function (known as "K combinator")
* No Church booleans
* No Church zero
* No Scott numerals
* No familiar list access primitives like <code>car</code>, <code>cdr</code> and <code>nth</code>

==Abstraction elimination rules==

As usual for languages of this family, abstraction elimination process is started from the most deeply nested lambda until no lambdas left. All free variables of the lambda in question are considered constants.

There are three approaches to abstraction elimination. They all share the same common property/drawback (which is a consequence of the chosen combinator basis): <code>λ x . CONST</code> can never be expressed in IJ basis. In practice it means that if your program needs it then you should look for alternative lambda expression for your program (see Examples section for the general idea how to do it).

===Rule 0: eta reduction===

It doesn't matter what approach is used, this is the only rule that actually eliminates an abstraction (i.e. gets rid of <code>λ</code> in an expression):

    λ x . F x ≡ F (if x is not used in F)

Important (and obvious) special case:

    λ x . x ≡ I

===Straighforward approach: BCS===

This approach uses known IJ expressions for <code>B</code>, <code>C</code> and <code>S</code> combinators:

    B = λ x y z . x (y z) = J(JII)(JI(JII))(J(J(JII)))
    C = λ x y z . x z y = J(JII)(J(JII))(J(JII))
    S = λ x y z . x z (y z) = J(J(JI(J(J(J(JII)))I)))I(J(JJII))JJ

====Rule 1: B rule====

    λ x . F G(x) ≡ B F (λ x . G(x)),  where G(x) is a function of x, F is not

Alternatively, it can be re-written using <code>Q</code> combinator (IJ expression for <code>Q</code> is a bit shorter):

    λ x . F G(x) ≡ Q (λ x . G(x)) F,  where Q = λ x y z . y (x z) = J(J(J(JII)))(JIII)(J(JI))

Even shorter IJ expression can be produced if this inlined version of <code>Q</code> combinator is used:

    Q x y = B y x = λ z . y (x z) = J (J I I) x (J I y)

====Rule 2: C rule====

    λ x . F(x) G ≡ C (λ x . F(x)) G,  where F(x) is a function of x, G is not

Alternatively, it can be re-written using <code>R</code> combinator (IJ expression for <code>R</code> is much shorter):

    λ x . F(x) G ≡ R G (λ x . F(x)),  where R = λ x y z . y z x = J(JII)

====Rule 3: S rule====

    λ x . F(x) G(x) ≡ S (λ x . F(x)) (λ x . G(x)),  where F(x) and G(x) are both functions of x

===BCS+===

This approach uses known IJ expressions for many common combinators, while using <code>B</code>, <code>C</code> and <code>S</code> rules as a fallback.

