===IJ approach===

This approach was developed specifically for IJ basis. The abstraction elimination is performed in the following order:

# Find the innermost lambda.
# Count a number of occurrences of bound variable.
# If no occurrences of bound variable are found in lambda expression then this lambda can't be expressed in IJ basis. '''ABORT'''
# If there's exactly one occurrence of bound variable, goto step 6.
# If there are more than one occurrences of bound variable, goto step 9.
# If bound variable is inside the ()-subexpression, it must be moved out using one or several applications of '''Q1 rule'''.
# If bound variable is not at the rightmost place of the expression then it must be moved there using '''T''', '''R''' and '''JR rules'''.
# Apply eta-reduction, repeat from step 1.
# Find any two occurrences of the bound variable (the closer to each other the better). If both occurrences share identical context (say, <code>J I I x</code> in both places), then the whole repeating subexpression can be deduplicated.
# Use permutating rules to move two occurrences of the variable to positions suitable for one of deduplicating rules (usually '''J-T deduplicating rule''' is the universal fallback).
# Apply deduplicating rule.
# Repeat from step 2.

====Permutating rules====

The aim of these rules is to move bound variable either to the rightmost position of the expression (to apply eta-reduction rule) or to a position suitable for one of deduplicating rules.

=====Q1 rule=====

This rule can be used to extract bound variable from ()-subexpression:

    a (x b) c d ... = Q1 a b x c d ...,  where Q1 = JI
       \                     ^
        \____________________|

Here's an example of multiple applications of the rule:

    a (x b c) d e ... = Q1 a c (x b) d e ... = Q1 (Q1 a c) b x d e ...

=====T rule=====

This rule can be used to move bound variable from the leftmost position to the right by 1 position:

    x a b ... = T a x b ...,  where T = JII
    \               ^
     \______________|

=====R rule=====

This rule can be used to move bound variable to the right by 1 position:

    a x b c d ... = R b a x c d ...,  where R = JT = J(JII)
      \                   ^
       \__________________|

=====JR rule ("castling move")=====

This rule can be used to move bound variable to the right by 2 positions. It's more compact that two application of R rule (5 combinators instead of 2x4):

    a x b c d e ... = J R c a b x d e ...
      \                         ^
       \________________________|

====Deduplicating rules====

All deduplicating rules are used to reduce number of occurrences of bound variable by 1.

=====J-T deduplicating rule=====

This is the most commonly used deduplicating rule:

    a x (b x c) d e ... = J (T x) a c b d e ...,  where T = JII

The important special case:

    a x (b x) c d ... = a x (T x b) c d ... = J (T x) a b T c d ...

=====J-R deduplicating rule=====

    a (b c x) x d e ... = J (R x) a c b d e ...

The important special cases:

    a x x = a (I I x) x = J (R x) a I I
    x x = I (I I x) x = J (R x) I I I
    x x x = J (R x) x I I = J (J T x) x I I = J (R x) J T J I I

=====J-Q1 deduplicating rule=====

Almost never happens to be applicable because no permutating rule can place bound variable to the leftmost place of subexpression. Nevertheless, the pattern may occur initially, so the rule exists:

    x (x (a b) c) d e ... = J (Q1 x) c a b d e ...

=====J deduplicating rule=====

Another almost-never-happening rule:

    x a (x b c) d e ... = J x a c b d e ...

